From 22c2de105060dede48098d337b908df5ebfd0e98 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sergey Fedorov <barracuda@macos-powerpc.org>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 14:14:42 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 01/10] fix(vendor): portability + CoreText groundwork for
 macOS 10.6 PowerPC
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Groundwork changes to the shared engine needed by the macOS-PPC port,
squashed from 7 original commits (upstream-history split into vendor/
frontend layers, 2026-07-21 — see the frontend branch for the accompanying
CONTOUR_FRONTEND_MACOS option this work was originally paired with).

- vtpty: fix the strerror_r return-type assumption in the ExitStatus
  formatter. The GNU (char*-returning) variant is glibc-only; Darwin, the
  BSDs and plain POSIX ship the XSI (int-returning) variant, where the
  message is written into the buffer. Select the GNU path only under glibc
  and use the XSI path (call for effect, format the buffer) everywhere else.
- CMake: apply -fexperimental-library only under Clang/AppleClang. It is a
  Clang/libc++ flag; GCC + libstdc++ builds (this port) do not understand it.
- text_shaper: build coretext_locator.mm and link CoreText/ApplicationServices
  correctly for 10.6 — CoreText became a standalone framework only in macOS
  10.8; before that its symbols/headers live in the ApplicationServices
  umbrella. ApplicationServices is always linked; -framework CoreText is
  added only where CMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET indicates it actually exists.
- crispy: aligned allocation without C11 aligned_alloc (not available on the
  older libc), and link libatomic on 32-bit where the toolchain needs it
  explicitly for the lock-free paths crispy uses.
- text_shaper/coretext_locator.mm: branch-by-branch stderr tracing to debug
  font/family resolution (kept — low-cost, useful for future 10.6 CoreText
  issues); resolve the font file path via ATS when kCTFontURLAttribute is
  null (a real 10.6 CoreText gap — see docs/coretext quirks); global
  CMAKE_OBJCXX_STANDARD=23 so this and other engine .mm sources compile
  against the same C++23 headers as the rest of the engine (a frontend .mm
  can still override to a lower per-source standard).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01LzTmVgP2ruMz987VJ78k77
